<DATE1>   7 January 1994 </DATE1>
<F P=100> Energy </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yanmar Diesel Engine Co. Receives Approval from CARB for </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yanmar Diesel Engine Co. Receives Approval from CARB for </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
Direct-Injection   Diesel Engine 

<F P=102> 94FE0402E Tokyo NIKKEI SANGYO SHIMBUN in Japanese 7 Jan 94 p 
2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 94FE0402E </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIKKEI SANGYO SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>
CSO 

  [Text] Yanmar Diesel Engine Co.'s direct-injection diesel 
engine passed the emissions criterion of the California 
Atmospheric Resources Bureau (CARB) and was approved by CARB. 
The engine keeps emissions down below the CARB standard because 
it has a smaller-diameter injection nozzle and improves the 
manner in which air is mixed with fuel. It is the first time in 
the world that a direct-injection diesel engine, in which fuel 
is directly injected into the cylinder, received approval. 
  The engine that passed the CARB criterion was the company's 
six-horsepower L70A engine, which is an improved version of the 
small, air-cooled L-A series diesel engines (3.5 - 10 
horsepower) that first appeared on the market in 1990. Starting 
with the L-A series engines, by June, Yanmar plans to get 
approval for its upright water-cooled diesel engines and 
mass-produce those that meet the emissions standards. 
  Small, general-purpose engines with less than 25 horsepower 
and engines for landscaping work will be subject to CARB's first 
set of regulations, which will go into effect in January 1995. 
After two years Yanmar aims to change all of its diesel engines 
that are subject to the regulations. The company will also 
tackle more development to deal with the even stricter second 
set of regulations CARB plans to put into effect in 1999. 

</TEXT>

