<HEADER>
<AU>   JPRS-JST-94-025L </AU>
JPRS 
Science &amp; Technology 

</HEADER>

<ABS>  Japan </ABS>
<DATE1>   14 April 1994 </DATE1>
<F P=100> Nuclear Technologies </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia Requests Japanese Cooperation for Development of </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russia Requests Japanese Cooperation for Development of </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
Plutonium   Annihilation Reactor 

<F P=102> 94P60229B Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 14 Apr 94 p 
7--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 94P60229B </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>
CSO 

  [Text] Nuclear Power Reactor Bureau Director Ermakov of 
Russia' s Ministry of Atomic Energy attended the annual meeting 
of the Japan Atomic Industrial Forum Inc. held 13-15 April 1994 
in Hiroshima. During a NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN press interview on 
the 13th, he disclosed that Russia is planning to request 
Japanese cooperation in the development of an advanced reactor. 
Russia wants to use the plutonium obtained through dismantling 
nuclear weapons for fuel. Russia soon will propose a 
cooperative arrangement through formal channels of the 
Japan-Russia Atomic Energy Agreement. 
  The cooperation request includes development of the 
800,000kW 
output ``BN-800'' fast breeder reactor. At present, its 
construction is temporarily on hold. They want to modify the 
existing core originally designed for fuel breeding to that for 
burning plutonium and long-life transuranium. They intend to 
process the plutonium produced through dismantling nuclear 
weapons in a way that will destroy it as it is burned as fuel. 
  Bureau Director Ermakov said, `They would like to promote 
development of the reactor as an international project along the 
lines of the International Tokamak Experimental Research.' 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

