<ABS>  Japan </ABS>
<DATE1>   18 April 1994 </DATE1>
<F P=100> Nuclear Technologies </F>
<H3> <TI>   JAERI Begins Safety Tests for US Next Generation Light Water </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    JAERI Begins Safety Tests for US Next Generation Light Water </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
Reactor 

<F P=102>   94P60229D Tokyo NIKKEI SANGYO SHIMBUN in Japanese 18 Apr 94 
p 5--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 94P60229D </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIKKEI SANGYO SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>
CSO 

  [Text] The Japan Atomic Energy Research Institute (JAERI) 
has begun the `ROSA-AP600' program in which safety experiments 
will be conducted for the U.S.'s next generation AP60() light 
water reactor. The JAERI, in collaboration with the U.S. Nuclear 
Regulatory Commission (NRC) , will conduct experiments 
simulating accidents using JAERI' s large-scale test facility 
(LSTF) . They will continue for one year to collect the basic 
data necessary to meet AP600 design qualifications. 
  The LSTF can simulate the functions of a pressurized water 
reactor (PWR) of 1. 1 millionkW output. The height and position 
of the equipment are almost the same as an actual PWR, but the 
volume is 1/48 that of an actual PWR. It can examine what 
occurs in the reactor at the time of the accident by simulating 
the coolant' s flow rates in the reactor. 
  The UPS. asked the JAERI in 1992 to make safety evaluations 
of the AP600 using their high performance LSTF, the world' s 
largest such facility. In response to the request, the JAERI 
modified the LSTF to conform to the structure of the gravity 
injection-type emergency core cooling system (ECCS) of the AP600 
and finally began experimenting. 
  The first experiment conducted on the 14th confirmed that 
the 
ECCS operated properly to cool down the core by simulating 
conditions under which a 2.5 cm diameter hole would develop in a 
pipe in the reactor. To collect comprehensive data, one test 
per month will be conducted hereafter by simulating conditions 
created by damage of much larger scale. 

</TEXT>

