<F P=100> Superconductivity </F>
<H3> <TI>   Small Antennas Using High-Tc Superconductors </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Small Antennas Using High-Tc Superconductors </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   43060060 Tokyo NTT REVIEW in English Nov 93 pp 69-73--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 43060060 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NTT REVIEW </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by Naobumi Suzuki, Keiichiro Itoh, Osamu Ishii, and </F>
Osamu Michikami] 
  [Text] This paper describes superconductive small 
antennas composed of helical coil elements and quarter-wave 
matching circuits. We obtained a high efficiency of 70% by 
using a 5OO MHz band one-element antenna with _l_/40 element. 
We 
also realized a unidirectional radiation pattern and a higher 
radiation efficiency than an equivalent Cu antenna by using a 
900 MHz band two-element superdirective antenna with a _l_/20 
element and a _l_/11 element spacing. We confirm that the use 
of 
superconductors and the present design principle are very 
effective for realizing of highly efficient small antennas. 
<H5>  Introduction </H5>
  Highly efficient small antennas are required for use as 
environmental monitors, which can detect long wavelength radio 
waves sensitively. However, the radiation resistance is very low 
in electrically small antennas, which have elements whose length 
is shorter than their wavelength. The radiation resistance of 
superdirective allay antennas, which have element spacings 
shorter than their wavelength, are also very low. Consequently, 
the loss resistance is relatively high and the radiation 
efficiency is very low when these small antennas are made of 
normal conductors. However, if a superconductor is used to 
fabricate small antennas, high efficiency can be maintained. 
Therefore, small antennas made of metal superconductors, such as 
lead, have been studied.[.sup]1,2[/] Although these antennas 
exhibited a lower antenna loss than equivalent antennas made of 
normal conductors, it was difficult to achieve a high absolute 
gain because they required the use of a cooling system with 
metal insulators, and this caused a decrease in antenna gain. 
  Since the discovery of high temperature superconductors 
(HTS), such as YBaCuO (YBCO) and BiSrCaCuO (BSCCO), many 
superconductive small antennas have been 
developed[.sup]3-5[/] because they only require simple 
cooling systems. This paper proposes small antennas made with 
HTS, which are composed of helical elements and quarter-wave 
matching circuits and a feed network.[.sup]6-9[/] The 
properties of these antennas are also described. 
<H5>  Antenna Structure </H5>
  Figure 1 (a) and (b) show the equivalent circuits of a 
one-element (a) and a two-element (b) antenna. 
I[.sub]n[/][.sup]e[/] (= 
_x_[.sub]n[/]I[.sub]0[/]exp(j¯[.sub]n[/]) where 
_x_[.sub]n[/], I[.sub]0[/], ¯[.sub]n[/] are real 
numbers) and R[.sub]n[/][.sup]in[/], are, respectively, 
the excitation currents and input resistance of the n-th element 
(n = 1, 2) which is self- resonating at a designed frequency. 
Z[.sub]cn[/][.sup]d[/], _a_[.sub]n[/][.sup]d[/] and 
L[.sub]n[/][.sup]d[/] are the characteristic impedance, 
attenuation constant and length of the matching circuit, 
respectively. Z[.sub]cn[/][.sup]d[/], 
_a_[.sub]n[/][.sup]d[/] and L[.sub]n[/][.sup]d[/] 
are attenuation constant and length of delay lines, 
respectively. Z[.sub]c[/][.sup]f[/] is the characteristic 
impedance of a feed line. The antenna is composed of a feed 
network which is composed of a feed line and delay lines, 
matching circuits and helical elements. Since 
R[.sub]n[/][.sup]in[/] values are generally much lower 
than Z[.sub]c[/][.sup]f[/] values, it is essential to 
match these impedances. _l_/4 matching circuits are used in 
these antennas, because they are easily formed using brittle 
sintered HTS. Self-resonant helical coils are used for the 
radiators,[.sup]10[/] because only the resistance (real part 
of the impedance) can be matched with a _l_/4 matching circuit. 
In order to adjust each I[.sub]n[/][.sup]e[/] to its 
designed value, Z[.sub]cn[/][.sup]m[/] and 
L[.sub]n[/][.sup]m[/] are determined while 
L[.sub]n[/][.sup]m[/] fixed at a quarter of an effective 
wavelength on a parallel line. Figure 2 shows the antennas made 
of HTS materials. Antennas A and B are 500 MHz band one-element 
antennas with elements which are _l_/40 in length and antenna C 
is a 900 MHz-band two- element end-fire superdirective array 
antenna with _l_/20 length element and a _l_/11 element 
spacing. 

<FIG ID=JPRS-JST-025L-52A>      Figure 1. Equivalent Circuits of Antennas </FIG>


<FIG ID=JPRS-JST-025L-52B>      Figure 2. Photograph of Antennas </FIG>


<H5>  2. One-Element Small Antenna </H5>
<H5>  2.1 Design and Fabrication </H5>
  The helical elements of antennas A and B in Figure 2 were 
designed to resonate at 500 MHz by using the moment 
method.[.sup]11[/] The directive gain of the radiators was 
calculated at 0.5 dBi. Figure 3 shows the loss at a helical 
element (_z_) as a function of element length (L[.sup]e[/]). 
When the surface resistance (R[.sub]s[/]) is large, 
_z_[.sup]e[/] increases rapidly as L[.sup]e[/] decreases. 
The elements of antennas A and B were made of sintered BSCCO, 
whose surface resistance was about 0.5 m_O_ at 500 MHz at 77 
K.[.sup]12[/] The _z_[.sup]r[/] values are therefore 
calculated to be about 0.4 dB in these elements. The input 
resistance of the element is calculated to be 0.37 _O_. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-JST-025L-53A>      Figure 3. Element Loss _z_[.sub]e[/], as a Function of </FIG>


  The matching circuit of antenna A was made of two Cu bars 
and 
a dielectric sheet (teflon) was placed between them. A parallel 
meander line made of EuBaCuO thin-films[.sup]13[/] was used 
for the matching circuit of antenna B in order to reduce the 
antenna size. The element and the matching circuit of both 
antennas were joined using silver paste. The loss of the Cu 
matching circuit of antenna A is not so high because the 
parallel line has a relatively large cross section.[.sup]7[/] 
By connecting the parallel line of the matching circuit to the 
microstripline of the feed network, the microstriplineworks as a 
balun (converter from balanced mode to unbalanced 
mode).[.sup]6[/] 
<H5>  2.2 Results and Discussion </H5>
  Figure 4 shows the actual gain of antenna A as a function of 
frequency. The gain of an equivalent Cu antenna is also shown in 
this figure for comparison. The actual gain of antenna A was 
-1.2 dBi at 80 K and 488 MHz and was 7.8 dB and 6.2 dB higher 
than the actual gain of the equivalent Cu antenna at room 
temperature (R.T.) and 77 K, respectively. This value 
corresponds to 70% of the radiation efficiency, and it is 
also 
very high compared with those of previously reported 
superconductive small antennas. The actual gain of antenna B was 
-4.5 dBi at 80 K and 469 MHz, and this value was 9.6 dB and 5.4 
dB higher than that of the equivalent Cu antenna at R.T. and 70 
K, respectively. This enabled us to confirm that these 
superconductive small antennas are more effective in realizing 
high-gain than a Cu small antenna. The relatively lower gain in 
antenna B is attributed to the loss at the joint between the 
helical element and the matching circuit. We believe that the 
gain will be improved by improving the joining method. 

<FIG ID=JPRS-JST-025L-53B>      Figure 4. Actual Gain of the Antennas </FIG>


<H5>  3. Superdirective Array Antenna </H5>
<H5>  3.1 Design and Fabrication </H5>
  In a two-element array antenna, the excitation current for 
each element, which leads to results in maximum gain, should be 
determined by solving the following of differential equations; 
  partialG[.sub]d[/]/partial 
I[.sub]n[/][.sup]r[/] = 0 (n = 1,2) 
  where G[.sub]d[/] is the directive gain of an antenna. If 
we assume that the resonant frequency is 900 MHz and the element 
spacing (d[.sub]e[/]) is 30 mm, relations between excitation 
currents (I[.sub]1[/], I[.sub]2[/]) of _x_[.sub]1[/] = 
_x_[.sub]2[/] and ¯[.sub]2[/] - ¯[.sub]1[/] = 
165.6Î are obtained.[.sup]2[/] The self- and 
mutual-impedances (Z[.sub]mn[/] n, m = 1, 2) of the elements 
are calculated by the moment method. The input impedances 
Z[.sub]n[/][.sup]in[/] (= 
R[.sub]n[/][.sup]in[/]+jX[.sub]n[/][.sup]in[/]) of 
the elements are computed by using Z[.sub]nm[/] and 
I[.sub]m[/]. In this antenna, we can theoretically expect a 
directive gain of 6.2 dBi, which is 5.3 dB higher than that of a 
one element antenna, and a front- to-back ratio of 7.9 dB in the 
radiation pattern. 
  Figure 5 shows the loss at the element of a 900 MHz band 
two-element array antenna as a function of d[.sub]e[/]. When 
R[.sup]s[/] is large, _z_[.sup]e[/] increases rapidly as 
d[.sub]e[/] decreases. As with antennas A and B the elements 
of antenna C were made of BSCCO. Since the surface resistance of 
BSCCO at 900 MHz and 80 K is 2 m_O_,[.sup]12[/] the loss was 
calculated at about 2.5 dB. The input resistance of each 
element, R[.sub]1[/][.sup]in[/] and 
R[.sub]2[/][.sup]in[/], was calculated at 2.0 _O_ and 
-1.66 _O_, respectively. The negative value of 
R[.sub]2[/][.sup]in[/] indicates that the element draws 
radiated power from the other element which has a positive 
R[.sub]1[/][.sup]in[/]. This is due to the strong mutual 
coupling between two elements placed closely each 
other.[.sup]14[/] Therefore, in order to obtain a theoretical 
antennagain, the power received at the negative 
R[.sub]2[/][.sup]in[/] element must be fed back to the 
positive R[.sub]1[/][.sup]in[/] element through the feed 
network. In order to realize the above feedback mechanism, the 
feed network must fulfill the following conditions; 
  (1) The difference in line length from the elements to the 
branch point must be equal to the phase difference between the 
excitation currents (¯[.sub]2[/]-¯[.sub]1[/]). 
  (2) The total line length between positive- and negative- 
R[.sup]in[/] elements via the branch point must also 
correspond to ¯[.sub]2[/]-¯[.sub]1[/] +/-„. 

<FIG ID=JPRS-JST-025L-54A>      Figure 5. Element Loss _z_[.sup]e[/], as a Function of </FIG>


  Consequently, L[.sub]n[/][.sup]d[/] is determined 
uniquely, and this is a particular feature of the superdirective 
array antenna.[.sup]9[/] The matching circuit of antenna C 
was made of sintered BSCCO, and the feed network was made using 
a conventional printed circuit board (_e_[.sub]r[/] = 10.2). 
The elements, the matching circuits and the feed network were 
joined together with silver paste. 
<H5>  3.2 Results and Discussion </H5>
  The actual gain of antenna C was -4.2 dBi at 910 MHz and 80 
K. Its gain was 5.4 dB and 4.0 dB higher than that of an 
equivalent Cu antenna at R.T. and 77 K, respectively. We 
therefore confirm that the superconductive small antenna 
exhibits a higher gain than a Cu antenna. Figure 6 shows the 
designed and measured radiation pattern of antenna C. Although 
unexpected radiations, which perhaps emanated from the feed 
system, were observed around _P_ = 205Î, a unidirectional 
radiation pattern and front-to-back ratio of 6.8 dB were 
confirmed for the antenna. The fact that the actual gain of 
antenna C was lower than the designed value seemed to result 
mainly from ohmic losses in the Cu lines and silver paste 
joints, and unwanted radiation. The gain should be improved by 
changing the feed network from normal conductors to 
superconductors. 

<FIG ID=JPRS-JST-025L-55A>      Figure 6. Designed and Measured Radiation Pattern of </FIG>


<H5>  Conclusion </H5>
  We proposed a design principle for superconductive small 
antennas with quarter-wavelength parallel line matching circuits 
and helical coil elements and/or a feed network. On the basis of 
this concept, we fabricated a 500 MHz-band one element antenna 
with a 0.025 _l_ radiator and 900 MHz band two-element end-fire 
superdirective array antenna with a 0.09 _l_ radiator spacing 
and 0.05 _l_ radiator length. These antennas exhibited a higher 
efficiency than an equivalent Cu antenna. We confirmed that the 
superconductor and the present antenna structures can be used to 
realize highly efficient small antennas. 
