<H3> <TI>   STA To Include SPring-8, COMETS in Supplementary Budget </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    STA To Include SPring-8, COMETS in Supplementary Budget </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   94FE0269B Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 29 Nov 93 p 
17 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 94FE0269B </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

<F P=106> [Article with no byline] </F>
  [Text] In the second modified budget to be submitted by the 
cabinet to the Diet on 30 November, the Science and Technology 
Agency (STA) included the expedited construction plans for two 
key projects -- SPring-8, a large radiating light facility, 
which is being constructed in the Harima Science Park City in 
Hyogo Prefecture, and the Communications and Broadcasting 
Engineering Test Satellite (COMETS), which is scheduled to be 
launched in FY96. 
  Both projects are being accelerated in the belief that they 
will contribute to the enrichment of the citizen's life, which 
is one of Prime Minister Hosokawa's key slogans. The STA 
modification budget is expected to run up to &yen;16.1 billion. 
  The budget for the radiating light facility includes about 
&yen;7 billion in electron beam accelerator construction costs. 
The facility is being constructed through a joint effort of the 
Japan Atomic Energy Research Institute (JAERI) and the Institute 
of Physical and Chemical Research (IPCR). It will accelerate 
electron beams to a speed close to the speed of light with a 
linear accelerator and a synchrotron, and the resulting 
radiating light that will be generated when the electron orbit 
is bent will be taken out as a beam line to be used for 
materials experiments and medical diagnoses. 
  STA included &yen;7 billion for the expedited construction 
of 
said facility even in the first modified budget and is going to 
allocate &yen;12.7 billion for the same purpose in the 
preliminary budget request for the next year. The modification 
budget this time will make sure at least a portion of it becomes 
usable in FY97. About &yen;6.2 billion has been budgeted for the 
development of COMETS to expedite the manufacture of the 
engineering model and the actual unit. The development of this 
satellite, intended for television broadcasting, was started in 
FY90. 

</TEXT>

